<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-267-190  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 267 190.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Feb 19 1990 v4 n7 p24(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Machines made for DBMS tasks. (database machines) (FEDSIMposium)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Jourdan, Ruby M.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Modern mainframe-based relational database management systems useup a considerable amount of the host processor's power and memory,and the wrong mix of CPUs, DBMS software and application systemscan slow performance, reduce data integrity and increase softwaremaintenance costs.andP;  Database machines are intended to provide moreefficient management of relational databases; the back-endprocessors connect to the mainframe and work as database serversin a networks of minicomputers and microcomputers.andP;  The relationalDBMS structure is built into the hardware for executing databasequeries and updating requests from the host; components of thesystems include all DBMS functions, the I/O offload processor,storage hardware and database and operating system software.andO;Advantages of database machines are described, and some vendors ofthe systems are listed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Data Base ServersDedicated ProcessorsRelational DBMSMainframe ComputersAdd-In-On DevicesEnhancementsProcessor SpeedSpecial-Purpose Computers.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>